The '''USCGC ''Saranac'' (1930)''' was a {{sclass-|Lake|cutter||USCG}} belonging to the [[United States Coast Guard]] launched on 12 April 1930 and commissioned on 2 October 1930.<ref name=USCG-Saranac>{{cite web|title=USCG Saranac|url=http://www.uscg.mil/history/webcutters/saranac_1930.pdf|website=USCG|publisher=US Coast Guard|accessdate=24 July 2015|date=17 November 2014}}</ref> After 11 years of service to the Coast Guard, she was transferred to the [[Royal Navy|British Royal Navy]] as part of the [[Lend-Lease Act]].

== Career ==
===Coast Guard - Saranac ===
After being commissioned 2 October 1930, ''Saranac'' was [[homeport|homeported]] in [[Galveston, Texas]] and participated in regular patrols.<ref name=USCG-Saranac/>

===Royal Navy - Banff ===
After being transferred to the British [[Royal Navy]] the newly named HMS ''Banff'' (Y 43) was commissioned on 30 Apr 1941 .<ref name=uboat-HMS>{{cite web|title=HMS Banff (Y 43)|url=http://www.uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/41.html|website=uboat.net|accessdate=24 July 2015}}</ref> On 8 Aug 1942, she rescued 18 people from the Norwegian tanker ''Mirlo'' which was torpedoed by [[German submarine U-130 (1941)|U-130]].<ref name=uboat-HMS/> On 27 February 1946 she was returned to the [[USCG]].

===Coast Guard - Sebec/Tampa ===

After the end of the [[World War II]], she was transferred back to the [[USCG]] on 27 February 1946. Initially given the name ''Sebec'' (WPG 164), she was renamed the ''Tampa'' before being commissioned 27 May 1947.<ref name=uboat-USCGC>{{cite web|title=USCGC Saranac|url=http://www.uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/11118.html|website=uboat.net|accessdate=24 July 2015}}</ref> 

